INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('52', '8', 'Eight-year-old girl banned from football tournament \'because she looks like a boy\'', 'Let\'s get this out of the way nice and early football officials - Girls can have any length hair they damn well want.\r\n\r\nMili Hernandez, who happens to have short hair, is a talented footballer who plays for girls team Omaha Azzuri Cachorros.  \r\n\r\nOver the weekend she and her team mates were disqualified from a tournament in Nebraska as officials believed she was a boy... Because of her hair.\r\n\r\nMili\'s family showed the officials her insurance card and a doctor’s physical form, which listed Hernandez as a female but it did little to sway the judgement of the officials.', 'images/image-50.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:55:54', null, 'post/52', 'images/postimages/image-50.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('53', '8', 'Manchester United won the Europa League and it was as emotionally charged as you\'d expect', 'On 22 May, at least 22 people were killed and 59 injured after a terrorist attack occurred during an Ariana Grande concert in Manchester.\r\n\r\nJust two days later, Manchester United played Ajax in the Europa League final in Stockholm. \r\n\r\nThanks to 17th and 46th minute goals from Paul Pogba and Henrikh Mkhitaryan, they won 2-0.\r\n\r\nAfter the game, the players expressed an awareness that this had been an emotional fixture.\r\n\r\nPaul Pogba, the first goal scorer and world-record transfer signing, said after the game:', 'images/image-51.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:56:01', null, 'post/53', 'images/postimages/image-51.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('54', '8', 'This sprinter is going viral for her perfect pre-race ritual', 'If running was all about style, this teen would be an Olympic Gold medallist.\r\n\r\nWhile lining up for a high school 100m race on Wednesday, Kelly Nicole Lopez did something a little more fun than usual when getting into the starting blocks.\r\n\r\nShe mixed up some gymnastics with her track and field and perfectly executed a flip back into a handstand before fitting her feet in the starting block.', 'images/image-52.png', '2017-07-15 12:56:10', null, 'post/54', 'images/postimages/image-52.png');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('55', '8', 'Orangemen played Curb Your Enthusiasm theme tune on Belfast march and everyone is very confused', 'A Twitter user named Patrick attended a Belfast march yesterday and there was something that took him rather by surprise. \r\n\r\nThe Twelfth of July parade celebrates the Protestant religion and heritage. Marchers this year were also commemerating the Boyne battle\'s 327th aniversary.\r\n\r\nPatrick, who was live tweeting his first ever march in Belfast, shared a video that shows the marching band playing what sounds to be the Curb Your Enthusiasm theme tune.', 'images/image-53.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:56:17', null, 'post/55', 'images/postimages/image-53.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('56', '8', 'Without Chance!', 'Samtredia was expected to face a tough opponent in Baku. This season showed that Qarabag Agdam is a “big fish” for us, but 0:5 are too much.\r\n\r\nIn the first 10 minutes the Turkish referee gave yellow cards to three Georgians football players and Qarabag scored a penalty.\r\n\r\nSamtredia did not have a chance during 90 minutes.\r\n\r\nIt was not that Samtredia which became champion last year. The current national championship proved that the club lacks Budu Zivzivadze, Bachana Arabuli and Lasha Shergelashvili. ', 'images/image-54.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:56:23', null, 'post/56', 'images/postimages/image-54.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('57', '8', 'We Are Far away from Modern Football', 'The Austrians scored the only goal by a beautiful combination at the beginning of the match.\r\n\r\nWe are far away from modern football. I am sure, individually, Dimitri Tatanashvili would have played better than forwards of Altach. Giorgi Ganugrava also started some good offences but could do nothing as there was no team action.\r\n\r\nAfter the match worldsport.ge asked Soso Pruidze: “Why cannot we play without ball? It was learnt in Paroe Islands, Malta, Luxembourg. They do it badly, but they do it. Why cannot we learn it?\r\n\r\nPruidze’s answer: “This is the most urgent question. Gia Geguchadze is a coach of U-21 team and he also says that we lack tactically educated players. It should come from children’s football. There are some players who want to work on it but nobody listens to them”.\r\n\r\nChikhura played actively only during 20-25 minutes after the goal. The Georgian club did not have a chance to score a goal in the second half.', 'images/image-55.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:56:29', null, 'post/57', 'images/postimages/image-55.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('58', '8', 'Europa League: Opponents of the Georgian Clubs', 'Europa League first and second qualifying round draws were held in UEFA headquarter in Nyon. The Georgian clubs will start participating from the first qualifying draw and all of them have tough opponents:\r\n\r\nChikhura (Georgia) – Altach (Austria)\r\n\r\nJagiellonia (Poland) – Dinamo Batumi (Georgia)\r\n\r\nTrencin (Slovakia) – Torpedo (Georgia)\r\n\r\nThe first qualifying round matches will be held on June 29 and July 6.', 'images/image-56.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:56:36', null, 'post/58', 'images/postimages/image-56.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('59', '8', 'Sanikidze May Miss EuroBasket', '\r\n\r\nViktor Sanikidze, member of the Georgia national basketball team, may miss EuroBasket 2017. Sanikidze has not practiced for several months due to leg injury. Viktor informed worldsport.ge about this information.\r\n\r\n“I have not started practicing due to leg injury. So, my chances to play at EuroBasket 2017 are 50X50”, - Sanikidze told us.\r\n\r\nBefore the start of 2016-2017 seasons Viktor transferred to Aris of Greece where he held few games. During one of the games he got injured and cannot practice.\r\n', 'images/image-57.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:56:43', null, 'post/59', 'images/postimages/image-57.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('60', '8', 'Gold, Silver and Bronze - the First Day of European Championship Finished in Georgian', 'Givi Macharashvili (96 kg), member of the Georgian youth freestyle wrestling team, is a champion of Europe. Champions and prize winners were revealed in four weight categories in Dortmund, Germany. The first day of the tournament finished with the Georgian anthem – Macharashvili beat Simone Iannattoni of Italy 10:0.\r\n\r\nGivi Macharashvili arrived in Germany as a silver medalist of the previous tournament. This year he defeated three opponents before the final: Dimitrios Akritidis of Greece (14:2), Magomedrasul Gazimagomedov of Azerbaijan (15:7) and Ibrahim Cipci of Turkey (14:5).\r\n\r\nEdem Bolkvadze (60 kg) and Nika Kenchadze (74 kg) also wrestled in the name of Georgia\r\n\r\nKenchadze took the second place and Bolkvadze took the third place.\r\n\r\nToday champions and prize winners will be revealed in other four weight categories. The following wrestlers will wrestle in the name of Georgia: Teimuraz Vanishvili (55 kg), Mirza Skhulukhia (66 kg), Zaur Beradze (84 kg) and Zuriko Urtashvili (120 kg).', 'images/image-58.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:56:51', null, 'post/60', 'images/postimages/image-58.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('61', '9', 'Koinari through, Moraa out in 200m races at Kasarani', 'Koinari, a form four student at Rirura Central Secondary School that has produced many middle and long distance track athletes, finished third in the third heat in a personal best of 21.79 to ease through to the semi-finals later Friday.\r\n\r\nKoinari finished behind the heat winner Luis Brandner from Germany in 21.23 (PB) and Vasyl Makukh from Ukraine in 21.62 (PB).\r\n\r\nFrenchman Paul Tritenne posted the fastest first round qualifying time with victory in the first heat of 21.08 followed by Brandner and the newly crowned 100m champion Tshenolo Lemao, who is chasing a double in 21.27.\r\n\r\n“There is no second chance and that is why my focus is firmly on winning gold for Kenya,” said the soft-spoken Koinari.', 'images/image-59.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:56:59', null, 'post/61', 'images/postimages/image-59.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('62', '9', 'Kandie, Bett ease into 2000m steeplechase final ', 'Kenya\'s Leonard Bett (left), Ethiopia\'s Girma Diriba (centre) and South Africa\'s Robert De Villiers lead the field in the 2000m steeplechase semi-finals during the IAAF World Under 18 Athletics Championships on July 14, 2017 at Moi International Sports Centre, Kasarani. PHOTO | CHRIS OMOLLO |\r\n\r\nThe first semi-final was basically a showdown between Kandie, who was suave over the barriers and the lanky Ethiopian Alemu Kitessa, who seemingly had problems at the barriers but good on the straight.', 'images/image-60.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:57:07', null, 'post/62', 'images/postimages/image-60.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('63', '9', 'Julius Yego: Ita Nao could have done better', 'Favourite Zhekai Liu from China lived to his billing to haul personal best 77.54m to win gold as South Africa’s Johannes Schlebusch settled for silver in 75.68. Another Chinese Quingshu Song took bronze in 73.64.\r\n\r\nYego said that there is great talent in the country but accused federation chiefs of not being keen on nurturing upcoming athletes.\r\n\r\n\"We have great talent in our country but the problem is that we don\'t have good facilities that will help the athletes in training. For instance, Leshan who is participating in javelin, is using wrong shoes which makes him not perform well,\" said Yego.\r\n\r\nAthletics Kenya Youth Committee chairman Barnabas Korir however said the training gears for the field events were bought but were not delivered on time.', 'images/image-61.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:57:15', null, 'post/63', 'images/postimages/image-61.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('64', '9', 'Make that 100-10! Kenya Simbas maul Tunisia at RFUEA', 'eighthman Joshua Chisanga, right wing Darwin Mukidza and blind side flanker Eric Kerre touched down a brace each to propel the Simbas to their largest ever victory in their history.\r\n\r\nMukidza stroked over back 11 conversions while centre David Ambunya, scrum-half Samson Onsomu, man-of-the match centre Leo Seje, Martin Owila and Steve Otieno helped themselves to a try each.\r\n\r\nSimbas led 46-10 at the break.\r\n\r\nBen Hamouda and Ashif Dhif managed the consolation tries for woeful Tunisia, who suffered their second defeat in the Gold Cup, having also fallen to Namibia 41-7 in Tunis the previous weekend.\r\n\r\nKenya, who had opened their campaign with a 33-33 draw with Uganda two weeks ago will meet Senegal in their third match in Saturday next week at the RFUEA grounds.\r\n\r\nKenya biggest win before Saturday’s match was 96-3 against Nigeria in 1987.\r\n\r\n“It’s a good victory but the battle has just started,” said Simbas coach Jerome Paarwater.\r\n\r\n“We still need to work on our defence and kick-offs which were not good.”\r\n\r\nPaarwater noted that they might have improved in their attack but their next opponents, who include Senegal, Zimbabwe and Namibia will pose a different challenge.\r\n\r\nTunisia flanker Saif Bousaada mourned the absence of most of their foreign-based players, who refused to travel over disagreement with their local federation\r\n\r\n“Kenya played a good and solid game. We are not embarrassed by the big loss,” said Bousaada. “It’s our regular players who refused to come who should be ashamed.”\r\n\r\nMousaada, who advised Kenya to inject more professionalism to their play if they want to harbour any hopes of beating Namibia.\r\n\r\nHe said that their chances of remaining in the group for next year’s 2019 World Cup qualifiers looked dim.\r\n\r\nOjee launched the Simbas hunt with a try that Mukidza converted before putting over a penalty. Mukidza was on the spot to convert his own try before converting Ambunya and Kerre’s tries for a Kenya 31-5 lead.\r\n\r\nHowever, Mukidza missed to convert Onsomu, Chisanga and Ojee’s second tries as the cruising hosts stretched their lead to 46-10 at the drinks.\r\n\r\nThe second half was one-way traffic with Ojee adding two more tries as Kerre and Mukidza completed their doubles.', 'images/image-62.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:57:25', null, 'post/64', 'images/postimages/image-62.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('65', '9', 'K’Opondo back as Kenya Simbas face Tunisia', 'North Africans, winning 46-15.\r\n\r\nThey met for the first time in 2005 where Kenyan triumphed 37-15 before meeting next in 2009 when Kenya lost 44-15. Kenya and Tunisia clashed at the 2011 final when Kenya won 16-7 at the RFUEA grounds.\r\n\r\nTheir next meeting was during the 2012 championship with Kenya claiming a 31-24 victory in the play-offs for third place.\r\n\r\nKenya suffered their heaviest defeat against Tunisia 52-5 back in 1997 when they met for the first time in a Test match.', 'images/image-63.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:57:35', null, 'post/65', 'images/postimages/image-63.jpg');
INSERT INTO `news` VALUES ('66', '9', 'Rooney, Everton delight fans in Tanzania', 'The Toffees received a warm welcome after arriving in Dar es Salaam on Wednesday with large numbers of Tanzanian football fans eager to greet Rooney and his new team-mates.\r\n\r\nIn May, Everton announced they had penned a five-year sponsorship deal with SportPesa to succeed Thai brewing company Chang.\r\n\r\n\"We\'re pleased to have secured the biggest commercial partnership deal in the club\'s history with an ambitious and growing, global company,\" Everton chief executive Robert Elstone said at the time.\r\n\r\n\"From the outset we have been impressed by SportPesa and the company\'s plans for the future. Over the coming months and years we will be working closely to realise our ambitions together.\"\r\n\r\n\"We are thrilled to have secured an alignment with Everton, a club weaved prominently throughout the tapestry of world football,\" added Ivo Bozukov, director of global strategy for SportPesa.\r\n\r\nSportPesa, which is looking to increase its visibility through the Premier League, is further strengthening its ties with the city of Liverpool by moving its European headquarters there.\r\n\r\nThe Kenyan company were Hull City\'s shirt sponsors last season, but the Tigers were relegated from the top flight at the end of the 2016-17 campaign. SportPesa also has partnerships with Arsenal and Southampton.', 'images/image-64.jpg', '2017-07-15 12:57:42', null, 'post/66', 'images/postimages/image-64.jpg');
